Dear Sen. M. Udall,

Thank you for your response. It is nice of you to write. But here is my rebuttal to the gun issue and I would appreciate it if this would be shared with all of your cohorts in the District of Columbia. 

Senator I do not know if you are aware of this but, when the second amendment was written, the “Designed for the battlefield” gun of the day was smoothbore flintlock musket, of a large caliber, with a .62 to .75 inch bore and virtually every American owned one. The two variants were the Brown Bess (British) and the Charleyville, a French musket used by the Americans. The government had muskets and so did the people. 

The musket used undersized tin (lead of the day) and they had to be reloaded after every shot. 

The musket of the 21st century happens to be the M16A1 carbine. So WE THE PEOPLE, HAVE, a natural UNALIENABLE right, not a privileged to keep them.

Where do you think America would be if the British would have had M16A1 carbines with 30 round magazines and our forefathers were left to fight with flintlock single shot muskets? You would be under a British occupation right now. 

Just as you and your cohorts are sewing to the American people, the British Government were attempting to interpose fraudulent British law onto the people who had no desire in partaking in the British system. People just wanted to govern themselves and be left alone.

The mere fact that you will go after gun owners vs. criminals who commit these mass shootings, who are on psychotropic drugs says enough. You will not even take a staunch stance on gang violence that has struck poverty stricken areas in the US. Most of those crimes involve guns too. What if our military was sent off to fight the coming war with the Muslim world and we were invaded by Russia or China? Sorry for my political incorrectness but China is a communist country, hence the term “Red China”. 

Did you know that before the bombing of Pearl Harbor, Japanese naval General Isoroku Yamamoto was quoted, saying the following; 

"You cannot invade the mainland United States. There would be a rifle behind every blade of grass." Isoroku Yamamoto, Commander-in-Chief of the Imperial Japanese Navy

That is fact, the Japanese Empire was planning to come in and conquer the entire CONUS. But was deterred because of one general that knew, behind every blade of grass, molecule of air, nook and cranny, Japan would find an American armed with a firearm, whether it be a full automatic Thompson, civilian, police pistol or military weapon; Gen. Yamamoto was sure that WE THE PEOPLE would give the Japanese military an absolute blood bath. 

So the fact that you are even alive to this very day and hold the office and titles you have acquired is directly contributed to two facts.  #1 WE THE PEOPLE let you and #2 the “battlefield type rifles” you are now today at war with, owned by us peasants actually deterred one of the most ruthless military’s on the face of the planet from invading this country.   

Whether the weapons are designed for the battlefield or not senator, it does not matter. Besides didn’t you and the rest of your criminal cohorts vote for the NDAA 2012 making the entire planet including the United States a battlefield? 

Wouldn’t it be appropriate for you to allow us to own firearms in the battlefield you have created? Do you see yourself above your wage payers?   Don’t you think we need weapons to protect ourselves in the utopian “battlefield” you and other cohorts have created in this country?

Senator, do you know what communist and fascist regimes do after the confiscation of firearms? They Kill, and Kill, and kill and when they get tired of killing innocent people, they kill some more. Innocent people in mass genocides die because they had no way to protect themselves from a tyrannical group of individuals posing as a legitimate government.   

I see you visited Afghanistan. Yet you were surrounded by the same type of firearms that you and your party are at war with now. Did you feel safe? See I too have been deployed multiple times, sometimes disarmed by my own government because they didn’t FEEL the need that we should carry M4’s with us. But regardless of where you or I went in the AOR, you are assigned a crack team of body guards carrying the same weapons you want to ban.  

I challenge you to go with no guns, or maybe a 5 round magazine. What’s that? Oh no response to your and your party’s hypocrisy. That’s what I thought. 

What do you plan to tell the men and women of The Watchmen of America and US Border Guard who volunteer to interdict drugs and stop illegal immigration on the border? They are just civilians, not government, not law enforcement just the people who have somehow, in your mind, stopped ruling over you. What do you plan to tell them when your party takes away their right to repel invasions of the United States? 

They are doing what the federal and state levels are failing to do. Your party now wants to make them a criminal because they have assault type SEMI AUTOMATIC rifles to defend this nation and there precious lives. Yet to complement their bravery and service the federal government gives the same drug cartels they fight, FULLY AUTOMATIC machine guns and explosives. Your own government officials died in the line of duty as well because of this anti-gun agenda. Yet no one goes to jail, no investigation, no nothing. 

What are you going to tell them UDALL? SENATORS, CONGRESSMEN, BARACK OBAMANATION? ANSWER THAT QUESTION………………. HMMMM Silence. 

Are you going to tell them that you don’t give two shits about supporting and defending the Document YOU JUST SWORE AN OATH TO A FRECKING WEEK AGO.  That would be the most honest thing I have heard from a politician in a long time. 

I have never seen more narcissism and lies culminate in one place and in such profusion. What is wrong with you people? Have you no honor? Have you no integrity? Have you no honesty? What about a soul? Do you even have one? None of you have a clue of what it means to serve with the above set of values. All that seems to show are three.

The Associated Press/The Huffington Post

WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Joe Biden on Wednesday heard personal stories of gun violence from representatives of victims groups and gun-safety organizations as he drafts the Obama administration's response to the shooting at a Connecticut elementary school. He pledged that action would be taken.

"I want to make it clear that we are not going to get caught up in the notion (that) unless we can do everything we're going to do nothing," Biden said. "It's critically important (that) we act."

The meeting was part of a series Biden is holding this week to build consensus around proposals to curb gun violence after the Dec. 14 shooting in Newtown, Conn. Twenty school children were killed.

The Huffington Post has obtained additional details about the meeting from a White House Pool Report. Biden, according to the report, explained that "the president IS going to act." The White House has determined that "executive action can be taken," stated the Vice President. The specifics of that action have not yet been settled.

Biden meets Thursday with the National Rifle Association and other gun-owner groups. Meetings with representatives of the video-game and entertainment industries also are planned.

President Barack Obama wants Biden to deliver policy proposals by the end of the month. Obama has vowed to move swiftly on the package, which is expected to include legislative proposals and executive action.


Participants in Wednesday's meeting with Biden included the Brady Campaign to End Gun Violence and groups from Arizona, Illinois and Wisconsin, states with spates of gun violence that garnered national attention, including the shooting in Arizona of then-Rep. Gabrielle Giffords. Also present were two survivors of the 2007 shooting at Virginia Tech that killed 32 people, as well as a stepfather of a victim of last July's massacre at a movie theater in Aurora, Colo., in which a dozen people were slain. Attorney General Eric Holder also attended.

But as the shock and sorrow over the Newtown, Conn., shooting fades, the tough fight facing the White House and gun-control backers is growing clearer. Gun-rights advocates, including the powerful NRA, are digging in against tighter gun restrictions, conservative groups are launching pro-gun initiatives and the Senate's top Republican has warned it could be spring before Congress begins considering any gun legislation.

"The biggest problem we have at the moment is spending and debt," Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell of Kentucky said this week. "That's going to dominate the Congress between now and the end of March. None of these issues will have the kind of priority as spending and debt over the next two or three months."

The killing of 6- and 7-year-olds at Newtown's Sandy Hook Elementary School appeared to stir a deep reaction from the White House and Capitol Hill. Obama pushed gun control to the top of his domestic agenda for the first time and pledged to put the full weight of his presidency behind the issue. Some Republican and conservative lawmakers with strong gun-rights records also took the extraordinary step of calling for a discussion on new measures.

But other gun-rights advocates have shown less flexibility. The NRA has rejected stricter gun legislation and suggested instead that the government put armed guards in every U.S. school as a way to curb violence. A coalition of conservative groups is also organizing a "Gun Appreciation Day" to coincide with Obama's inauguration this month.

The president hopes to announce his administration's next steps to tackle gun violence shortly after he is sworn in for a second term on Jan. 21.

Obama wants Congress to reinstate a ban on military-style assault weapons, close loopholes that allow gun buyers to skirt background checks and restrict high-capacity magazines. Other recommendations to the Biden group include making gun-trafficking a felony, getting the Justice Department to prosecute people caught lying on gun background-check forms and ordering federal agencies to send data to the National Gun Background Check Database.

Some of those steps could be taken through executive action, without the approval of Congress. White House officials say Obama will not finalize any actions until receiving Biden's recommendations.

Gun-rights lawmakers and outside groups have insisted that any policy response also include an examination of mental health policies and the impact of violent movies and video games. To those people, the White House has pledged a comprehensive response.

"It is not a problem that can be solved by any specific action or single action that the government might take," said White House spokesman Jay Carney said. "It's a problem that encompasses issues of mental health, of education, as well as access to guns."

In addition to Biden's meetings this week, Education Secretary Arne Duncan will meet with parent and teacher groups, and Health and Human Services Secretary Kathleen Sebelius will meet with mental health and disability advocates.

The White House said other meetings are also scheduled with community organizations, business owners and religious leaders.

___

Associated Press writer Darlene Superville contributed to this report.
